<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 94 / International Company News: US retailer emerges from Chapter
11
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Herman's Sporting Goods, the ill-starred US sporting goods retailer, has
emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy and plans to expand. Herman's is owned by
an investor group led by the New York merchant banks Whitman Heffernan Rhein
and Carl Marks.
The group bought Herman's in March 1993 and put it into Chapter 11 three
days later.
Herman's was originally acquired by the UK's Dee Corp (now Gateway) in 1986
for Pounds 278m (Dollars 439.2m), and promptly went into loss as a result of
ill-judged expansion. Gateway was taken over in 1989 in the UK's largest
buy-out, and attempts were made to sell Herman's. The eventual sale price
was believed to have been about Dollars 40m.
The new owners have used bankruptcy protection to return Herman's to its
stronghold in the north-east states, closing all stores west of Pennsylvania
and south of Virginia.
