<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 94 / UK Company News: Hi-Tec Sports shares dive 33p - Warning
that margins will continue to slide follows losses of Pounds 7m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Hi-Tec Sports tumbled by 33p to 45p yesterday as the sports shoe
and leisure wear company reported a fall into headline losses in the six
months to July 31 and suggested that margins would continue to slide until
at least the spring of 1995.
In a period of significant changes within the group, pre-tax profits of
Pounds 776,000 were turned into losses of Pounds 7.11m after exceptional
charges of Pounds 5.91m and interest payable Pounds 401,000 higher at Pounds
1.54m.
The restructuring was now over, said Mr Frank van Wezel, chairman and 53.19
per cent shareholder, and the loss-making activities had been 'dealt with'.
Apart from the closure of the European subsidiaries, the most important
event has been the disposal of 60 per cent of Cofex, the Dutch company which
makes fashion jackets under the Bad Boys brand name. In the period it
incurred unchanged trading losses of Pounds 1.95m, and accounted for Pounds
202,000 of interest charges and Pounds 5.1m in respect of goodwill
previously written off.
Mr van Wezel said that the losses this time masked underlying growth in the
the group's core rugged outdoor footwear and were different from the
recessionary losses of two years ago.
Group turnover edged ahead to Pounds 60.4m (Pounds 59.4m), including Pounds
3.73m from discontinued operations. On continuing activities, margins were
down about 2 per cent across the group. Stripping out Cofex, pre-tax profits
fell to Pounds 1m (Pounds 2.9m) on turnover up at Pounds 56.7m (Pounds
53.9m).
Mr Peter Butler said that having never been properly monitored, group stock
was now being managed at lower levels and that these stock reductions would
continue. Stock provisions had been raised by Pounds 500,000. Discounting
seasonal swings, debt had been reduced by Pounds 5.1m to Pounds 21.3m.
In North America, operating profits fell to Pounds 1.2m (Pounds 2m) on
turnover of Pounds 23.2m (Pounds 23.6m). Mr van Wezel said a sudden fall-off
in the fashionability of the Magnum law enforcement boots among urban youth
disguised a 22 per cent rise in sales of the core hiking boots. There was
also a hiatus when the group repositioned its products and withdrew them
from discount retailers. Some Pounds 4m of sales were lost.
In the UK and Ireland profits eased by Pounds 100,000 to Pounds 700,000 on
sales up 9 per cent to Pounds 21.6m. Sales of brown boots rose from 12 to 19
per cent of the total. South Africa did well since the elections, accounting
for some Pounds 5m of the rest of the world's Pounds 8.2m (Pounds 6.8m)
total. Profits were Pounds 500,000 (Pounds 700,000).
The group has changed its auditor from KPMG Peat Marwick to Touche Ross. It
has also changed its year-end from January 31, 'in the middle of our
delivery season' to April 30.
The interim dividend is 1.6p (1.25p), increased for the 15-month period. The
directors are taking up the scrip alternative, so the cash element is
covered 1.4 times, even though losses were 15.6p (earnings 1.4p) per share.
Forecasts for the year to January 31 have fallen to Pounds 2m or earnings of
3p, for a prospective multiple of 15.
</TEXT>
