FT  01 OCT 94 / UK Company News: Union Square rights and reconstruction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Union Square, the property investment and development group which suffered
heavily in the commercial property slump of the early 1990s, yesterday
announced a rights issue and capital reconstruction.
In a statement issued after the market closed, the group said it hoped to
raise Pounds 9.6m from a 1-for-1 rights issue at 5p per share. The shares
closed unchanged at 9p.
The move is designed to reduced the group's reliance on Thompson
Investments, its ultimate holding company, which last year advanced loans of
Pounds 10.8m to cover its debts.
Mr Richard Thompson, chairman of Union Square and managing director of
Thompson Investments, said the rights issue would increase shareholders'
funds to about Pounds 10.5m and would clear the way for a capital
reconstruction.
'Thompson Investments will swap their debt for equity, leaving it with a 79
per cent stake,' he added.
In the year to March 31, the property company made pre-tax profits of Pounds
212,000 (Pounds 83,000) on turnover of Pounds 3.81m (Pounds 1.75m),
including Pounds 2.36m from disposals.
Although dividends have been unpaid since 1990, Mr Thompson - also a
director of Queen's Park Rangers football club - forecast a resumption of
payments 'in a year or two'.
