<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 94 / Sub-postmasters seek sale pledge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Financial Times Reporter
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sub-postmasters yesterday demanded assurances that the Counters subsidiary
of the Post Office would not be 'asset-stripped' in order to benefit the
Royal Mail and Parcelforce divisions of the organisation.
The National Federation of Sub-Postmasters was commenting on government
plans to sell 51 per cent of Royal Mail and Parcelforce while keeping
Counters in the public sector. Yesterday was the deadline for comments on
the plans.
Mr Colin Baker, federation general secretary, said the government's
proposals for Counters could mean a more secure future for sub-postmasters
with opportunities for business growth.
'However, the fact remains that not all sub-offices can offer all
transactions - and that rural sub-offices in particular continue to close as
their viability is in doubt,' he added.
Strong support for the government plans came yesterday from the
Confederation of British Industry, which said the commercial freedom
generated by privatisation was critical to the future success of the postal
service because it faced stiff international competition.
Privatisation would 'bring further price and quality improvements benefiting
customers', the CBI added. New competitive pressures on providers of postal
services would benefit customers.
'Every business uses postal services, and for many companies the postal bill
is a major overhead,' the CBI said.
However, the unions and opposition parties are resolutely opposed to
privatisation in any form, repeating the stance they have taken with
virtually every privatisation over the last decade - most of which they no
longer propose to reverse.
Union and Labour leaders have highlighted the dramatic pay rises for senior
managers which have followed earlier privatisations. They also claim the
sell-off might endanger the letters service, and the 20,000 rural post
offices.
The 51 per cent sale of Royal Mail and Parcelforce is the government's
favoured option. About 10 per cent of the privatised company would be sold
to Post Office employees and to the staff managing sub post offices run on
contract for the Post Office.
</TEXT>
