<HEADLINE>
FT  01 OCT 94 / Japan and US edge towards trade pact
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US and Japanese trade negotiators yesterday headed into a final day of talks
to open Japan's markets to US goods and services, having achieved 'big
progress' on government procurement.
A Japanese trade official in Washington said only one or two issues were
outstanding in the dispute over Japanese government purchases of
telecommunications and medical equipment. He said these could be settled
with the help of Mr Yohei Kono, Japan's foreign minister, who arrived in
Washington yesterday afternoon. Agreement was also near on US access to
Japan's insurance market.
Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US Treasury secretary, said: 'There is much yet to be
done.'
A Tokyo news report saying that the US and Japan had reached a deal on
procurement helped the dollar climb briefly above Y99 yesterday, but
official denials later wiped out some of the US currency's gains. It closed
in London at Y98.97, up from Thursday's close of Y98.505.
Rumours of a deal helped the London equity market, which closed 33.8 points
up at 3,026.3, also boosted by reports of a Pounds 100m buying programme
from an investment bank. In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average
closed 11.44 points lower at 3,843.19.
However, US and Japanese negotiators have been pessimistic about reaching a
deal on cars and car parts. If no vehicle deal is reached, the US is
expected to list car parts and flat glass as posing a barrier to US trade.
World stocks, Page 19
Lex, Page 22
